{
  "text": "The composition and the functional moieties present in N-CNTs were analyzed by using the XPS. It provides detailed information on the occupied electronic levels and chemical binding states of individual atoms. The Gaussian multi-peak reveals the individual nitrogen moieties bonded to the carbon atoms in CNTs. XPS-wide spectrum showed strong peak at 285, 401 and 530 eV which can be assigned to C1s from sp 2 hybridized carbon in the nanotubes; the carbon atoms on the edge plane can be easily oxidized to oxygen-containing functionalities and nitrogen incorporated in carbon network, respectively. The asymmetric N1s peak in narrow spectrum centered at 401 eV can be deconvoluted into four peaks at 398.5, 401, 403 and 405 eV [CITATION_1] . They are ascribed as pyridine-like nitrogen (pN), graphitic-like nitrogen (gN), oxidized nitrogen and molecular nitrogen. 398.5 eV peak is assigned to a tetragonal nitrogen phase bonded to a sp 3 hybridized carbon, 401 eV assigned to a trigonal nitrogen phase bonded to a sp 2 coordinated carbon, 403 eV is assigned to oxidized N species or oxygen molecules physisorbed onto the rough surface and 405 eV is assigned to molecular nitrogen molecules adsorbed or intercalated at the carbon walls or trapped in the compartments.",
  "citation_candidates": [
